We would like to invite you to the debate called ‚ÄúGlobal Race in Emerging Technologies Deployment: Lessons for EU-Pacific Cooperation‚Äù in the EU-PACIFIC Talks series.
The debate will take place online on Tuesday, January 9 at 11:00.
---------------
Speakers:
üü¢ Ciar√°n Humphreys, Research Fellow, Cleantech, Financial Instruments for Climate
üü¢ Jannik Jansen, Policy Fellow, Jacques Delors Centre, Hertie School

üéôÔ∏è Rebeka Hengalov√°, Research Fellow, EUROPEUM Institute for European Policy
---------------
In navigating the global race in emerging technologies influenced by the Inflation Reduction Act, Net Zero Industry Act, and Green Transformation Act, it is evident that nations are at a crossroads of opportunity and challenge. This debate offers valuable insights for discussions on EU-Pacific cooperation particularly in navigating the complexities of international rivalry, protectionism, and the pursuit of sustainable and cooperative approaches to addressing climate change and transitioning to a net-zero economy

ad_creative_link_descriptions:
We would like to invite you to the debate called ‚ÄúCharting the course for Ukraine: Reassessment of the Indo-Pacific‚Äù in the EU-PACIFIC Talks series.
The debate will take place online on Tuesday, November 28 at 13:00.
---------------
Speakers:
üü¢‚Äã Benedetta Girardi, Strategic Analyst, The Hague Centre for Strategic Studies
üü¢ Kurai Takashi, Former Ambassador of Japan to Ukraine
üü¢ Benjamin Tallis, Senior Research Fellow, German Council on Foreign Relations

üéôÔ∏è Moderator: Danielle Piatkiewicz, Research Fellow, EUROPEUM Institute for European Policy
---------------
A profound impact of Russia's attack on Ukraine has been the rallying of support from various countries, demonstrating their willingness to aid in Ukraine's recovery. At its core, this multilateral vision is driven by the collective understanding that Ukraine's future is inseparably tied to global peace and security. Central and Eastern European countries, in particular, provided logistical, weapons, and displacement support and helped change the security narrative. In light of greater engagement in the region, the question arises whether the Indo-Pacific remains the primary battlefield for major power competition. Examining the lessons from the Ukrainian conflict, the discussion delves into the potential impact on Indo-Pacific dynamics and the capacity of European allies and partners like the US to navigate their commitments in the Indo-Pacific.
---------------
We will be broadcasting the event live, and you can watch the live stream here on the event page. You will be able to join the discussion directly during the debate by commenting below the video.
If you already have any questions, please post them in the discussion section of this event.
The live stream and a recording of the discussion will also be available here: https://www.facebook.com/europeumprague/live/.

ad_creative_link_descriptions:
We would like to invite you to the debate called ‚ÄúEU-Pacific Talks: The weaponization of information: The future of risk in digital era?‚Äù in the EU-PACIFIC Talks series.
The debate will take place online on Tuesday, October 24 at 13:00.
---------------
Speakers:
üü¢‚Äã Mark√©ta Gregorov√°, Member of the European Parliament, Pirates, Group of the Greens/European Free Alliance
üü¢‚Äã Kyoko Kuwahara, Research Fellow, Japan Institute of International Affairs
üü¢‚Äã Linda Monsees, Senior Researcher, Institute of International Relations, Prague

üéôÔ∏è Moderator: Danielle Piatkiewicz, Research Fellow, EUROPEUM Institute for European Policy
---------------
The weaponization of information, particularly through social media platforms, has proved to be a significant challenge in the last decade. The lack of effective regulation and oversight over these platforms has contributed to the spread of disinformation. Various regions have faced disinformation campaigns and cybersecurity threats to influence public opinion, manipulate election outcomes, and undermine democratic processes. Taiwan serves as a notable case study in the realm of cybersecurity. Taiwan has been at the forefront of dealing with the weaponization of information and cybersecurity threats mainly propagated by China. This session will discuss how certain countries' experiences with disinformation campaigns and their proactive approaches to countering them, along with their focus on cybersecurity, provide valuable insights and serve as models for addressing these challenges.
---------------
We will be broadcasting the event live, and you can watch the live stream here on the event page. You will be able to join the discussion directly during the debate by commenting below the video.
If you already have any questions, please post them in the discussion section of this event.
The live stream and a recording of the discussion will also be available here: https://www.facebook.com/europeumprague/live/.

ad_creative_link_descriptions:
We would like to invite you to the debate "EU Enlargement to the Western Balkans: 20 Years After the Thessaloniki Summit", which will take place on October 16th at 17:00 on the premises of the University of Economics in Prague in room NB 169 (Rectors¬¥ Lounge). Address: Churchill 4, Prague 130 67. 

The debate is organised by EUROPEUM Institute for European Policy, Centre for European Studies V≈†E and Faculty of International Relations of the University of Economics in Prague /FMV/. 

To participate in person, please register here: https://forms.gle/3jWedMGeGSimncYd8

The online stream will be available on our Facebook event and on the Facebook page of the Centrum evropsk√Ωch studi√≠ V≈†E / Centre for European Studies V≈†E.
----------------------
Speakers:
üü¢ Othon Anastasakis, Director of the European Studies Centre and Director of South East European Studies, St Antony‚Äôs College, University of Oxford
üü¢ Jana Juzov√°, Senior Research Fellow and Head of Global Europe Programme, EUROPEUM Institute for European Policy
üü¢ Rikard Jozwiak, Europe Editor, Radio Free Europe / Radio Liberty

üéôÔ∏èModerator: Jarol√≠m Antal, Director of Centre for European Studies, Prague University of Economics and Business
-------------------------
The Western Balkans countries were promised a future within the European Union in June 2003. Over the twenty years, the EU integration of this region has been marked by a lack of progress in reforms on the side of the candidates for EU membership and repeated blocking of the process on the side of individual EU Member States, resulting in mutual distrust and frustrations. However, the Russian war of aggression against Ukraine put the EU enlargement process in a new context, providing a new impetus for restoring the Union‚Äôs credibility in its immediate neighbourhoods. 

Is there actually a new momentum in the process of the EU enlargement? Will the fast advancement of Ukraine and Moldova toward EU integration motivate the Western Balkans to kick-start the necessary reforms, or will it deepen the mistrust of the region toward the Union? Is the EU ready to accept new members? Should the enlargement process be reformed in order to restore the EU‚Äôs transformative power?
--------------------
We look forward to seeing you.

ad_creative_link_descriptions:
We would like to invite you to the debate called ‚ÄúEU-Pacific Talks: Taiwan and security dimension ‚Äì lessons learned, Indo-Pacific containment‚Äù in the EU-PACIFIC Talks series.
The debate will take place online on Friday, October 6 at 14:00.
---------------
Speakers:
üü¢‚Äã Jonas Parello-Plesner, Executive Director, Alliance of Democracies Foundation
üü¢ ‚ÄãBonji Ohara, Senior Fellow, Security Studies Program, Sasakawa Peace Foundation
üü¢ ‚ÄãJustyna Szczudlik, Deputy Head of Research, China Analyst, Polish Institute of International Affairs

Moderator:
üéôÔ∏è Alexandra Visnerova, Senior Project Manager, EUROPEUM
---------------
Unpacking Taiwan‚Äôs security environment and lessons from its situation remain crucial in understanding the context of Indo-Pacific containments. Due to its geostrategic location and complicated relationship with the People‚Äôs Republic of China (PRC), Taiwan‚Äôs security has become a significant concern for regional stability. This session will discuss the strategic importance of Taiwan‚Äôs geographical and geopolitical role within the context of relations with China as well as Indo-Pacific containment, where several countries, most notably the United States, Japan and Australia, have sought to counterbalance China‚Äôs growing influence and assertiveness in the region. Understanding Taiwan‚Äôs security dimension provides valuable lessons in understanding the importance of its strategic location, the need for military preparedness, the diplomatic challenges it faces, and its role within the broader context of Indo-Pacific containment efforts.
---------------
We will be broadcasting the event live, and you can watch the live stream here on the event page. You will be able to join the discussion directly during the debate by commenting below the video.
If you already have any questions, please post them in the discussion section of this event.
The live stream and a recording of the discussion will also be available here: https://www.facebook.com/europeumprague/live/.

ad_creative_link_descriptions:
We would like to invite you to the debate called "EU-Pacific Talks: In-EV-itable future of automotive industry: what is the role of the Pacific region" in the EU-PACIFIC Talks series.

The debate will take place online on Tuesday, May 30 at 13:00.
Over the course of 6 months, the most tempting issues will be on the table, such as the relationship between the EU and ASEAN, the new security environment, trade, nuclear energy, and the automotive industry.
--------------------
Speakers:
üîµ Michal Hrub√Ω, Scientific Assistant, ≈†KODA AUTO University
üîµ Petr Knap, Lead Partner for Mobility & Advanced Manufacturing in the Czech Republic, and Mobility Leader for Central and Eastern Europe, Ernst & Young Czech Republic
üîµ Jin Kusaka, Professor, Graduate School of Environment and Energy Engineering, Waseda University, Japan

üéôÔ∏è Moderator: Alexandra Visnerova, Senior Project Manager,
EUROPEUM Institute for European Policy
---------------------------
Global value chains were hit hard by both COVID-19 and the war initiated by Russia. Although previously not visible to everyone, the supply side in the automotive industry is strongly interconnected. Amid the ongoing crisis, its sustainability transformation might now be at risk of delay. Electric and fuel cell vehicles, both foreseen as a way of road transport decarbonization, are both raw material-intensive and, hence, not the cheapest solution to passenger mobility. The assumptions of continuous decrease in the price of batteries and the reaching of price parity between internal combustion engine vehicles and electric vehicles are tested. Yet, the urgency of transport decarbonization has never been stronger. How can the pioneering country of hybrid, partly electrified, vehicles and fuel cell vehicles, Japan, help the EU to successfully transform its fleet and improve urban planning with the deployment of light vehicles? Are both these regions ready for a massive uptake of electric vehicles on the way to 2035?
----------------------
We will be broadcasting the event live and you can watch the live stream here on the event page. You will be able to join the discussion directly during the debate by commenting below the video.
If you already have any questions, please post them in the discussion section of this event.
The live stream and a recording of the discussion will also be available here: https://www.facebook.com/europeumprague/live/.

ad_creative_link_descriptions:
We would like to invite you to the debate called "Be small and beautiful - future of nuclear energy?" in the EU-PACIFIC Talks series.
The debate will take place online on Tuesday, March 28 at 15:00.
Over the course of 6 months, the most tempting issues will be on the table, such as the relationship between the EU and ASEAN, the new security environment, trade, nuclear energy, and the automotive industry.
--------------------
Speakers:
üîµ Aliki van Heek, Unit Head 3E Analysis, IAEA 
üîµ Ewa Lazarczyk Carlson, Associate Professor, Reykjavik University, SIF
üîµ Okamoto Koji, Professor, Graduate School of Engineering, The University of Tokyo
üîµ Radek ≈†koda, Professor/Head of Energy 4.0, CIIRC, Czech Technical University in Prague

üéôÔ∏è Moderator: Michal Hrub√Ω, Economist, International Sustainable Finance Centre (ISFC)
---------------------------
Although it is a challenge to convey the message of its safety to the public, nuclear energy is perceived as an essential part of low-carbon energy solutions to reach net-zero targets in 2050. V4 countries mostly do rely on nuclear power plants in order to boost their electricity base load. Japan foresees the future of nuclear energy in the deployment of the next generation of nuclear technologies, including small modular reactors and a new generation of pressurized water reactors, different from the type that operated in Fukushima. While the Chernobyl and Fukushima experiences still invoke distrust and apprehension, nuclear fusion has the potential to be a reliable, CO2-free source of energy. The advancements in nuclear fusion technologies do promise to deliver a successful net-zero energy transformation ‚Äì however, costs remain a significant concern, particularly as renewables become increasingly competitive. Is the future of nuclear energy to be found in smaller modular reactors? How could this impact the V4?
----------------------
We will be broadcasting the event live and you can watch the live stream here on the event page. You will be able to join the discussion directly during the debate by commenting below the video.

If you already have any questions, please post them in the discussion section of this event.

The live stream and a recording of the discussion will also be available here: https://www.facebook.com/europeumprague/live/.

2022 marks 45 years of partnership between the EU and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN). Elevated to a strategic partnership in 2020 and cemented with the EU Strategy for Cooperation in the Indo-Pacific in 2021, the EU has bolstered relations over the last four decades with strong economic, trade, and political ties. The Austro-French Center, the Institut Montaigne, Europeum Institute for European Policy, GLOBSEC, the French Embassy to Austria, the Austrian Society for European Politics cordially invite you to a discussion on the topic of:

Building up European sovereignty has been the golden thread of President Emmanuel Macron‚Äôs European policy since his speeches at La Sorbonne, Athens, Strasbourg, and Aix- la-Chapelle. It has also been a priority of the French Presidency of the Council, which now comes to an end. Its motto, ‚Äúrecovery, power, belonging‚Äù, echoed the debates launched in the framework of the Conference on the future of Europe, and conveyed aspirations that the EU should gain in strategic autonomy.

Russia‚Äôs brutal invasion of Ukraine has now put this vision of Europe to a severe test, forcing the Union to effectively respond to the greatest challenge posed to its security and values. The EU does not start from an advantageous position. The economic crisis, Brexit, tensions among the Member states, populism, and the Covid-pandemic have already eroded its stamina. But the salience of this existential threat, with its far-reaching implications, is of game-changing significance. With the Russian invasion of Ukraine, the vision advocated by France, Germany, and others of a Europe that bears its future in its hands is more pressing than ever.

As the French Presidency of the Council comes to an end, what assessment can be done of the past six months? How has the war affected the priorities of the French Presidency and the EU in general? How does it reflect on the discussions on the future of Europe? What geopolitical implications will it have on the world stage? And how can the EU square the circle of values vs. geopolitical interests in its security engagement? What contribution can the Czech Presidency seek to make?

ad_creative_link_descriptions:
On behalf of EUROPEUM Institute for European Policy we would like to cordially invite you to a discussion titled "Asylum and migration policy: Danish and Czech perspectives". The event is organized in cooperation with the Embassy of Denmark in Prague.

Registration link for the debate: https://bit.ly/37IOKV6

Speakers:
üîµ Karol√≠na Kottov√°, Deputy Head of Representation and Head of Political Section, Permanent Representation of the European Commission, Prague
üîµ Clotilde Warin, Advisor on European Affairs at the Centre for Analysis, Planning and Strategy of the Ministry for Europe and Foreign Affairs, France
üîµ Henrik Ankerstjerne, Deputy Permanent Secretary, Ministry of Immigration and Integration of Denmark
üîµ Tom√°≈° Urubek, Department of Asylum and Migration Policy, Ministry of Interior of the Czech Republic
üîµ Magda Faltov√°, Director, Association for Integration and Migration, Prague

üéôÔ∏è Moderator: Filip Nerad, Analyst, ƒåesk√Ω rozhlas

Since the ‚Äòmigration crisis‚Äô of 2015-16, migration has remained one of the most contested issues in European policy. Several attempts at reviving the Common European Asylum System (CEAS) have failed due to irreconcilable divergences amongst Member States, and the New Pact on Migration and Asylum has similarly failed to generate momentum for long-term sustainable solutions. 

Because of this deadlock, Member States have begun exploring unilateral or bilateral solutions in lieu of European ones. Denmark, a country renowned for its relatively expansive migration policy in the past, has tightened its policy gradually since the crisis, adopting a modus operandi of ‚Äúskirting the edges of the international conventions.‚Äù Some of these provisions are now being given exception due to the war in Ukraine.  
The war in Ukraine has generated a profound solidarity within Europe as Ukrainians flee by the millions. Whether this heralds a more fundamental paradigm shift remains to be seen; despite the current solidarity, the Belarus crisis that preceded it exposed European vulnerabilities to migration in general, and weaponized migration by malign foreign actors in particular. The EU and its Member States will have to balance security concerns with respect for universal human rights and international obligations. 

This debate will explore the Danish migration policy and its wider European ramifications. Has Denmark found a viable blueprint for tackling migration holistically?  Has the Danish approach of ‚Äúskirting the edges of the international conventions‚Äù been successful in adhering to obligations under those conventions? What can the Czech Republic take away from this approach and what should be the migration policy of the new Czech government as it faces an unprecedented number of Ukrainian refugees? Is the EU facing a fundamental paradigm shift in its migration and asylum policy?

---

The discussion would take place on Thursday, April 21, 2022 from 16:00 at the European House (Jungmannova 745/24, 110 00) and it will be also live-streamed on our Facebook page.

‚è∞ Tuesday, 5 April from 10:30.
üìåAt Prague Creative Centre (room 219 / online).

The European security paradigm has changed dramatically with Russia‚Äôs invasion of Ukraine. Our perceptions of European security and a host of other areas, including digitalization, shifted.

Digitalization plays an increasingly important role in conflicts. Its role will only grow in the coming years as European countries look toward new growth drivers, shoring up their digital resilience and security, and digitalizing and transforming their public services.

However, this further exposes countries, businesses, and individuals alike to a new kind of cyber and information threats. We now worry about cyberattacks and digital warfare, potentially crippling important infrastructure and services, and eroding the cohesion of our democratic societies. Several EU member states ‚Äì France, Germany, and the Netherlands ‚Äì as well as the bloc itself have announced their strategy for the Indo-Pacific in the past years. The Indo-Pacific, a vast region spanning from Africa's east coast to the Pacific islands, has become increasingly strategic. After four decades of relative peace, it has turned into a prime area for strategic competition. The U.S.-China rivalry is reshaping the balance of power at play. Military budgets are growing and tensions in so-called grey zones are intensifying.

We would like to invite you to the debate  called "Norway and the Czech Republic ‚Äì Challenges on the Way to Sustainability and Decarbonization" 

The debate will take place online on Thursday 11 November at 18:00.

In December 2020 the heads of the EU Member States decided that the Union will become a climate-neutral economy by the end of 2050. The states simultaneously tasked the European Commission to propose a plan that will facilitate implementation of the new EU climate target, which subsequently happened in the form of the Fit for 55 Package ‚Äì a significant step towards climate neutrality.

Even the best policy, however, is deemed to fail when not supported by the local population. Policy makers must always respect limits of changes they can impose on the citizens so that they support the new direction and do not divert to anti-system parties. In this respect we will introduce the initial position of Norwegians and Czechs with respect to economy transformation.

What do Norwegians and Czech think about sustainability and decarbonization? How willing are they to alter their behavior? And which obstacles lie ahead of sustainable and carbon-free future regarding public opinion?

üî¥Moderation: Kate≈ôina Davidov√°, Centre for Transport and Energy

ad_creative_link_descriptions:
We would like to invite you to the first of six debates in the EU-PACIFIC Talks series. The debate will take place online on Tuesday 21 September at 14:00.  

Over the course of 6 months, the most tempting issues will be on the table, such as growing influence of China, climate agenda, economic relations or the United States new administration.

Confirmed speaker:
üî¥ Takashi Hosoda, Visiting Lecturer, Faculty of Social Science, Charles University

üîµ Andrew Small, Senior Transatlantic Fellow, Asia Program, German Marshall Fund of the United States

üü† Ivana Kar√°skov√°, Analyst, Association for International Affairs - AMO

üü¢ Moderation: Danielle Piatkiewicz, Research Fellow, EUROPEUM Institute for European Policy

-----------------
Concerns over China's growing influence has been tied to their eagerness to take its place as a global leader on issues such as technology, trade, security, economic and even climate issues. While at the same time, challenging the shared values and the rules-based international order that link democracies like Japan and the EU together. To add to this complexity, the EU and their long-time partner the US, have often taken diverging approaches on dealing with Beijing, often playing into the hands of China. As China seeks to both invest but also divide the region, the EU will need to continue to balance this relationship by keeping their friends close, but foes closer. 
-----------------
We will be broadcasting the event live and you can watch the live stream here on the event page. You will be able to join the discussion directly during the debate by commenting below the video. If you already have any questions, please post them in the discussion section of this event.
The live stream and a recording of the discussion will also be available here: https://www.facebook.com/europeumprague/live/.

The EU and the US have a strong incentive to work on a joint strategy which would target it on a transatlantic level. NATO could be an important forum and an amplifier of such efforts, given its ongoing work and expertise in the cyber security domain. 

What is the current state of American and European resilience to the disinformation threat? How do nations and platforms build a resilient society together? Why and in what ways are the malign actors successful, whether it be a focus on citizens or attacks on sensitive infrastructure? ad_creative_link_descriptions:
We would like to invite you to the event organized by the Think Visegrad platform which brings together 8 think-tanks from Central Europe.

According to the EU's 5G Action Plan, 5G Networks were supposed to be launched in all EU Member States by the end of 2020. However, due to several reasons, 5G Networks became a controversial topic, that often divides public opinion. What is the current situation over 5G networks in Europe? How are V4 countries acting in regards to this technology? Is 5G posing security threats and why did it become a victim of various conspiracy and disinformation theories? And how can disinformation, often rife on social media, be effectively combatted in order to ensure democratic integrity?

According to the EU's 5G Action Plan, 5G Networks were supposed to be launched in all EU Member States by the end of 2020. However, due to several reasons, 5G Networks became a controversial topic, that often divides public opinion. What is the current situation over 5G networks in Europe? How are V4 countries acting in regards to this technology? Is 5G posing security threats and why did it become a victim of various conspiracy and disinformation theories? ad_creative_link_descriptions:
Join this year's last EU¬± online debate with a special guest ‚Äì Lu√≠s de Almeida Sampaio, Ambassador of Portugal to the Czech Republic.

In January 2021, Portugal takes over the Presidency of the EU Council. Simultaneously, the Czech presidency in 2022 is quickly approaching. Although the silence in the media might suggest otherwise, the Czech preparations are in full swing, making the debate a great opportunity to discuss what challenges small and mid-size EU states face while holding the EU presidency. 

Another topic to cover is how the COVID-19 pandemic influences the Portuguese presidency and what lessons the Czech Republic should take from the Portuguese experience.
